   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1842-09_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <salute>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p><note>62</note>
               <note>1842</note><lb/>
               know then that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL1">Lucy</persName>and<persName ref="./personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName><lb/>
               <persName ref="./personography.xml#EdgeF3">(M<hi rend="superscript">rs.</hi>Wilson)</persName> are now both well<lb/>
               and they and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM2">Packenham</persName><lb/>
               and the Butlers &amp; the Fox<lb/>
               children all having been<lb/>
               with us round <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs.</hi>Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
               This summer have made<lb/>
               it a memorable summer<lb/>
               for happiness to which we shall<lb/>
               look back with pleasure all<lb/>
               the rest of our lives<lb/>
            </p>
            <p><quote>You may break, you may injure<lb/>
                  the vase as you will<lb/>
                  But the smell of the roses will stick<lb/>
                  to it still</quote><lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs.</hi>Edgeworth</persName> has perfectly<lb/>
               recovered her health this year<lb/>
               after the severe rheumatic<lb/>
               fever she had last year - She is<lb/>
               now not only as strong and<lb/>
               active as ever but almost with<lb/>
               as fresh a bloom in her cheeks<lb/>
               which seems like the expression<lb/>
               of mind that never fades-<lb/>
               Her silver grey hairs both contrast<lb/>
               <note>? Sept 1842.</note>
            </p>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1842-09_page02.jpg"/>
            <p><note>1842</note><lb/>
               and suit her whole <choice><orig>appear<lb/>
                  -ance</orig><reg>appearance</reg></choice> - 
               <choice><orig>shewing</orig>
                  <reg>showing</reg></choice> <del>how to be</del><lb/>
               without admixture or <choice><orig>adop-<lb/>
                  tion</orig><reg>adoption</reg></choice> of fake hair that she<lb/>
               has no desire to <hi rend="underline">appear</hi>young<lb/>
               but that the real freshness<lb/>
               of youth is preserved in her<lb/>
               by nature -<lb/>
            </p>
               <p>So much for boasting of<lb/>
               one's own family - please<lb/>
               to burn - &amp; consider it as<lb/>
               not my own <persName ref="./Personography.xml/#EdgeA2">mother</persName> I am<lb/>
               boasting of but my<persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2"><choice><orig>stepmo-<lb/>
                  ther</orig>
                  <reg>stepmother</reg></choice></persName> - &amp; 
               my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1"></persName><choice><orig>fathers</orig>
                  <reg>father's</reg></choice> widow<lb/>
               after 25 years widowhood &amp;<lb/>
               after our having lived together<lb/>
               upwards of 44 years -<lb/>
               a good spice of truth must have<lb/>
               been in that friendship to<lb/>
               make it keep so long - &amp; not<lb/>
               a bit stale now - &amp; if <hi rend="underline">iced</hi><lb/>
               only with sugar -<lb/>
            </p>
         </div>
